text:
This film is really... wow...Pros;
Tim Robbin's Andy Dufrense is a unique yet compelling lead character. The way that Robbin performs him, you really can't tell whether he is a sociopathic innocent or a psychopath in general.As always Morgan Freeman is great. The casting director clearly knew this as Freeman plays Red: an elder-like character who imparts wisdom about prison life but also clever and witty. Also, his narration over much of the film is great too (Thanks to his great voice).The supporting cast are also really nice but the stand out is James Whitmore's Brooks for his emotional packing. Despite having a large amount of supporting characters, they all shine in their own way and despite little screen time, all actors leave their mark.The story (Much thanks to being adapted from Stephen Kings' book of the same name) is really polished and every single element has a payoff as the narrative continues.As previously touched upon, the film packs a large amount of emotion and stays with the audience very much.Cons;
Pfft. I guess that this was a box office failure when it came out? Well, if you were alive in 1994 and don't watch this: shame on you.Verdict;
With a suburb cast, compelling character and clever narrative, The Shawshank's Redemption is a film worth watching if ever you get the chance.
